00:00:22.250 --> 00:00:27.290
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: So class
1 as you all will recall

00:00:27.290 --> 00:00:29.960
was about direct
innovation factors.

00:00:29.960 --> 00:00:34.550
And we looked at the growth
economists, Solow and Romer

00:00:34.550 --> 00:00:35.270
in particular.

00:00:35.270 --> 00:00:39.050
And they essentially gave us
two direct innovation factors

00:00:39.050 --> 00:00:42.830
that you really can't account
for in an innovation system

00:00:42.830 --> 00:00:44.270
unless those are inputs.

00:00:44.270 --> 00:00:48.680
So what we could
translate Solow as saying,

00:00:48.680 --> 00:00:54.080
you need to do R&D. And we
can translate Romer as saying,

00:00:54.080 --> 00:00:56.660
you need to--

00:00:56.660 --> 00:00:58.610
it's the talent in
the system that's

00:00:58.610 --> 00:01:02.150
working in this system
that's a critical input.

00:01:02.150 --> 00:01:04.550
So that gives us our first
two innovation factors.

00:01:04.550 --> 00:01:08.000
Class 2 brought us our third.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:12.080
And we began to consider
innovation as not just factors,

00:01:12.080 --> 00:01:13.790
but as a system.

00:01:13.790 --> 00:01:16.580
And Liz Reynolds' discussion
earlier this afternoon

00:01:16.580 --> 00:01:20.520
was a good reminder of a
systems approach to innovation.

00:01:20.520 --> 00:01:22.820
So we read Richard
Nelson, and he

00:01:22.820 --> 00:01:29.978
introduced the idea of looking
at national innovation systems.

00:01:29.978 --> 00:01:31.520
He wasn't the first
to use that term.

00:01:31.520 --> 00:01:33.228
Chris Freeman at the
University of Sussex

00:01:33.228 --> 00:01:36.590
was, but he really
explored the dimensions

00:01:36.590 --> 00:01:38.660
and taught us to look
at the innovation

00:01:38.660 --> 00:01:42.890
institutions and the
strengths and weaknesses

00:01:42.890 --> 00:01:44.750
of those institutions.

00:01:44.750 --> 00:01:46.670
And with that
concept then, you can

00:01:46.670 --> 00:01:50.180
begin to explore any
innovation system.

00:01:50.180 --> 00:01:54.320
Our third direct
innovation factor,

00:01:54.320 --> 00:01:57.050
then, is really all about
innovation organization.

00:01:57.050 --> 00:02:00.900
The strength of the actors, the
connections between the actors,

00:02:00.900 --> 00:02:04.220
and then the gaps in
that innovation system.

00:02:04.220 --> 00:02:06.350
You can analyze all of
those and understand a lot

00:02:06.350 --> 00:02:08.570
about the strength of a
particular innovation system,

00:02:08.570 --> 00:02:10.460
whether it's national,
whether it's regional,

00:02:10.460 --> 00:02:12.110
whether it's local.

00:02:12.110 --> 00:02:15.380
And Liz gave you a
reading of her study

00:02:15.380 --> 00:02:16.880
of the state of
Massachusetts, which

00:02:16.880 --> 00:02:20.570
is a good glimpse
into those issues.

00:02:20.570 --> 00:02:23.900
So classes 3 and 4 I
won't recap because Liz

00:02:23.900 --> 00:02:25.760
gave us a good reminder
of those issues.

00:02:25.760 --> 00:02:29.300
But we studied manufacturing,
and how it evolved

00:02:29.300 --> 00:02:30.410
in two different periods--

00:02:30.410 --> 00:02:33.890
both the 1980s competition
period and the current decline

00:02:33.890 --> 00:02:36.350
of US manufacturing in the
first decade of this century,

00:02:36.350 --> 00:02:39.510
the early 2000s.

00:02:39.510 --> 00:02:41.660
And that was a good
case study for us

00:02:41.660 --> 00:02:44.540
on how to take these
ideas of innovation system

00:02:44.540 --> 00:02:48.620
and look at a system,
the manufacturing system.

00:02:48.620 --> 00:02:52.820
Class 5 pulled back and
got us into the framework

00:02:52.820 --> 00:02:59.360
again, looking at innovation
at the institutional level.

00:02:59.360 --> 00:03:05.870
How does R and D and
prototype, how do those stages

00:03:05.870 --> 00:03:08.890
operate in innovation
organizations, R

00:03:08.890 --> 00:03:10.190
and D organizations?

00:03:10.190 --> 00:03:11.690
And then, how does
the handoff occur

00:03:11.690 --> 00:03:14.023
in an innovation system and
the strength of those actors

00:03:14.023 --> 00:03:15.110
as well?

00:03:15.110 --> 00:03:18.530
So that got us into thinking
about looking at innovation

00:03:18.530 --> 00:03:20.270
at the institutional level.

00:03:20.270 --> 00:03:23.690
Class number six was about
the Valley of Death problem.

00:03:23.690 --> 00:03:27.740
The gap that was in effect
built in into the US innovation

00:03:27.740 --> 00:03:32.540
system because we focused
the federal role on research,

00:03:32.540 --> 00:03:35.240
it didn't really focus on
the follow-on later stage

00:03:35.240 --> 00:03:37.580
development in
subsequent stages, right?

00:03:37.580 --> 00:03:40.640
So it guaranteed a gap
between our innovation actors,

00:03:40.640 --> 00:03:43.940
between the research world
and the implementation world.

00:03:46.850 --> 00:03:54.620
And we talked about innovation
at the face-to-face level.

00:03:54.620 --> 00:03:57.970
So innovation doesn't just occur
at the institutional level,

00:03:57.970 --> 00:03:59.150
it occurs amongst people.

00:03:59.150 --> 00:04:01.910
People innovate,
not institutions.

00:04:01.910 --> 00:04:04.280
Institutions help organize
an innovation system,

00:04:04.280 --> 00:04:05.810
but in the end it's people.

00:04:05.810 --> 00:04:10.370
And what are the rule sets that
govern the way innovation looks

00:04:10.370 --> 00:04:13.590
like at the face-to-face level?

00:04:13.590 --> 00:04:16.279
And we got deeply into
great group theory.

00:04:16.279 --> 00:04:18.200
Class number 8 was
about DARPA, which

00:04:18.200 --> 00:04:23.870
is a very different innovation
model than the bulk of the US

00:04:23.870 --> 00:04:25.697
system, organized around--

00:04:25.697 --> 00:04:28.280
predominately around they end
of the World War II time period.

00:04:30.853 --> 00:04:32.270
It's an organization
that attempts

00:04:32.270 --> 00:04:36.260
to combine capabilities at
both the institutional level,

00:04:36.260 --> 00:04:40.130
but also the great
group forming innovation

00:04:40.130 --> 00:04:41.720
at the face-to-face level.

00:04:41.720 --> 00:04:43.430
Working on
breakthrough technology

00:04:43.430 --> 00:04:45.603
is what DARPA calls
a right/left model.

00:04:45.603 --> 00:04:47.270
It wants to think
about what it gets out

00:04:47.270 --> 00:04:49.080
of the end of the
innovation system.

00:04:49.080 --> 00:04:52.460
It's not just curiosity-driven.

00:04:52.460 --> 00:04:54.590
So what do they
want, and then how

00:04:54.590 --> 00:04:56.630
to go back to the early
stages and develop

00:04:56.630 --> 00:04:58.730
the breakthroughs to get there?

00:04:58.730 --> 00:05:01.490
So a very different
organizational model.

00:05:01.490 --> 00:05:04.840
Class 9 was a case study on NIH.

00:05:04.840 --> 00:05:07.550
And again it brought
home to us how

00:05:07.550 --> 00:05:12.420
to look at an innovation
system, in this case,

00:05:12.420 --> 00:05:14.630
in the life science
research world.

00:05:14.630 --> 00:05:18.190
And what are the institutional
barriers and problems

00:05:18.190 --> 00:05:19.660
in that system?

00:05:19.660 --> 00:05:22.750
Class 10 was around
energy technology,

00:05:22.750 --> 00:05:27.160
we introduced the idea of
the difficulty of innovating

00:05:27.160 --> 00:05:30.130
in a legacy economic sector--

00:05:30.130 --> 00:05:33.520
and established,
complex, existing legacy

00:05:33.520 --> 00:05:37.690
sector that builds up its
own paradigm to protect

00:05:37.690 --> 00:05:40.350
its models that
are technological,

00:05:40.350 --> 00:05:43.900
they are economic, they are
political, they are social.

00:05:43.900 --> 00:05:46.720
And they build barriers
to disruptive threats

00:05:46.720 --> 00:05:49.300
from the outside,
from new entrants

00:05:49.300 --> 00:05:51.670
that would attempt to
disrupt that model.

00:05:51.670 --> 00:05:54.235
And how do you begin to think
about bringing innovation

00:05:54.235 --> 00:05:57.373
into these legacy sectors is
a really important question,

00:05:57.373 --> 00:05:59.290
because most of the
economy is legacy sectors.

00:05:59.290 --> 00:06:03.190
And if you're walling off
80% or more of your economy

00:06:03.190 --> 00:06:05.770
from innovation, then you're
going to dramatically affect

00:06:05.770 --> 00:06:08.200
your ability to grow,
and your growth rate,

00:06:08.200 --> 00:06:09.700
and your societal well-being.

00:06:09.700 --> 00:06:13.960
So in effect that's the
problem with legacy sectors,

00:06:13.960 --> 00:06:14.870
and that's the need--

00:06:14.870 --> 00:06:16.662
that's the reason why
we need to figure out

00:06:16.662 --> 00:06:18.460
how to innovate in them.

00:06:18.460 --> 00:06:22.480
Class 11 was all
about education.

00:06:22.480 --> 00:06:25.110
Again, another legacy sector.

00:06:25.110 --> 00:06:27.370
And we talked about
a whole set of ways

00:06:27.370 --> 00:06:31.270
to think about science
education, technology

00:06:31.270 --> 00:06:34.240
education, and then education
for innovation itself.

00:06:34.240 --> 00:06:38.410
Could we ever attempt to
think about that as a teaching

00:06:38.410 --> 00:06:39.460
approach?

00:06:39.460 --> 00:06:42.040
And today will be all about
the future work, which

00:06:42.040 --> 00:06:46.840
I think is an issue that is
going to affect all of you,

00:06:46.840 --> 00:06:50.500
and will kind of dominate
a lot of your time

00:06:50.500 --> 00:06:51.920
over ensuing decades.

00:06:51.920 --> 00:06:54.640
So we're going to try and sort
this one out and try and figure

00:06:54.640 --> 00:06:57.130
out what it means by
reading some of the leading

00:06:57.130 --> 00:06:59.650
thinkers in this area.

00:06:59.650 --> 00:07:05.260
And then Liz was great
by doing the whole--

00:07:05.260 --> 00:07:06.640
innovation is like real estate.

00:07:06.640 --> 00:07:08.450
It's location,
location, location.

00:07:08.450 --> 00:07:12.317
So it really forms in
these geographic regions.

00:07:12.317 --> 00:07:14.650
You really need to understand
it in geographical region.

00:07:14.650 --> 00:07:16.460
We didn't have time for
everything in this class,

00:07:16.460 --> 00:07:17.740
but that's certainly one
of the classes I would

00:07:17.740 --> 00:07:19.540
have added if I had the time.

00:07:19.540 --> 00:07:24.070
So Liz walked us through some
of those initial concepts

00:07:24.070 --> 00:07:26.500
in that field, which she does
really important work in,

00:07:26.500 --> 00:07:28.150
by the way.

00:07:28.150 --> 00:07:31.600
All right you've got
Brynjolffson Johnson

00:07:31.600 --> 00:07:33.730
and you've got the
first David Autor piece.

00:07:33.730 --> 00:07:36.490
So why don't I do
those together,

00:07:36.490 --> 00:07:38.830
because they're they
critique each other, right?

00:07:41.520 --> 00:07:45.370
And this is a big debate that's
going on, on the MIT campus

00:07:45.370 --> 00:07:49.810
with different perspectives
here as we're going to see,

00:07:49.810 --> 00:07:52.660
about what's going to
happen to work here.

00:07:52.660 --> 00:07:57.400
And so after the
Great Recession,

00:07:57.400 --> 00:07:59.840
the economy went through
a very slow period

00:07:59.840 --> 00:08:01.930
of putting people back to work.

00:08:01.930 --> 00:08:07.210
Now, we're now back to
5% or lower employment,

00:08:07.210 --> 00:08:10.810
but we still have a large number
of people that never went back

00:08:10.810 --> 00:08:12.400
into the workforce.

00:08:12.400 --> 00:08:14.960
A shockingly high number.

00:08:14.960 --> 00:08:17.540
So this problem-- we're
not past this problem.

00:08:17.540 --> 00:08:21.440
So this is an early piece by
Erik Brynjolffson and Andrew

00:08:21.440 --> 00:08:21.940
McAfee.

00:08:21.940 --> 00:08:22.990
AUDIENCE: Sorry.

00:08:22.990 --> 00:08:24.160
Brynjolffson.

00:08:24.160 --> 00:08:25.630
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
Brynjolffson.

00:08:25.630 --> 00:08:26.330
Forgive me, Tom.

00:08:26.330 --> 00:08:27.330
AUDIENCE: Just in case--

00:08:27.330 --> 00:08:28.350
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
No, I appreciate it.

00:08:28.350 --> 00:08:30.070
I'm glad we're going
to get that right.

00:08:30.070 --> 00:08:30.790
AUDIENCE: Brynjolffson.

00:08:30.790 --> 00:08:31.900
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
Brynjolfsson.

00:08:31.900 --> 00:08:32.400
All right.

00:08:32.400 --> 00:08:34.330
Good.

00:08:34.330 --> 00:08:35.789
So Eric and Andrew--

00:08:35.789 --> 00:08:41.320
how's that-- brought us a
whole set of new thinking

00:08:41.320 --> 00:08:42.555
about this territory.

00:08:42.555 --> 00:08:44.680
And there's a debate about
what their findings are.

00:08:44.680 --> 00:08:47.470
This is an early
piece they produced.

00:08:47.470 --> 00:08:51.760
Their book on this topic is
called The Second Machine Age.

00:08:51.760 --> 00:08:53.530
So they looked at
this problem of why

00:08:53.530 --> 00:08:55.240
wasn't the economy
putting people back

00:08:55.240 --> 00:08:59.530
to work at a rate that
was more acceptable?

00:08:59.530 --> 00:09:03.760
And they argued that
the 2007, 2008 recession

00:09:03.760 --> 00:09:07.450
wasn't a typical
business cycle recession.

00:09:07.450 --> 00:09:10.960
In other words, you didn't lose
your job and then get it back.

00:09:10.960 --> 00:09:13.190
You lost your job, period.

00:09:13.190 --> 00:09:14.320
Right?

00:09:14.320 --> 00:09:17.110
Your job did not come
back after this recession,

00:09:17.110 --> 00:09:19.390
in many sectors,
particularly manufacturing

00:09:19.390 --> 00:09:21.760
as we talked about.

00:09:21.760 --> 00:09:25.060
So one explanation was, gee,
it's just not a normal business

00:09:25.060 --> 00:09:27.340
cycle.

00:09:27.340 --> 00:09:29.590
It's stagnation.

00:09:29.590 --> 00:09:32.770
And there's a long-term
decline in certain sectors

00:09:32.770 --> 00:09:34.750
that you have to
understand and look at.

00:09:34.750 --> 00:09:40.150
A third explanation, which
they venture to set out,

00:09:40.150 --> 00:09:43.720
was that it wasn't
really stagnation either,

00:09:43.720 --> 00:09:46.300
and it wasn't too
little innovation--

00:09:46.300 --> 00:09:47.920
a signal of stagnation--

00:09:47.920 --> 00:09:52.210
it was too much
innovation for the economy

00:09:52.210 --> 00:09:54.010
to manage and handle.

00:09:54.010 --> 00:09:55.900
And so they embarked,
then, on kind

00:09:55.900 --> 00:10:01.700
of a history of this concern
about the end of work,

00:10:01.700 --> 00:10:05.050
which they argue started
in 1995 with a growing

00:10:05.050 --> 00:10:09.460
concern at that time about
technological job displacement.

00:10:09.460 --> 00:10:11.410
And they look at the
surrounding technologies

00:10:11.410 --> 00:10:13.000
that are emerging--

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:18.010
Google's driverless
cars, Watson's Jeopardy,

00:10:18.010 --> 00:10:22.420
Ray Kurzwell, in his book,
The Age of Spiritual Machines:

00:10:22.420 --> 00:10:25.030
When Computers Exceed
Human Intelligence,

00:10:25.030 --> 00:10:27.705
began to portray some
of these concerns.

00:10:27.705 --> 00:10:29.830
In other words, people were
going to get displaced.

00:10:29.830 --> 00:10:31.990
Their work was going
to be displaced

00:10:31.990 --> 00:10:36.100
by the advent of the IT
technology revolution

00:10:36.100 --> 00:10:41.560
as it moves into artificial
intelligence areas.

00:10:41.560 --> 00:10:45.070
What is clear is that there
has been exponential growth

00:10:45.070 --> 00:10:47.380
in the computing sector.

00:10:47.380 --> 00:10:49.150
And computers are
thousands of times

00:10:49.150 --> 00:10:53.380
better than they
were 30 years ago.

00:10:53.380 --> 00:10:57.430
But there are areas that
Eric and Andrew point out,

00:10:57.430 --> 00:11:01.090
where computers are not
good at particularly

00:11:01.090 --> 00:11:06.630
the sort of combination of both
physical and knowledge areas,

00:11:06.630 --> 00:11:09.218
and are not yet good at
general problem solving,

00:11:09.218 --> 00:11:11.010
and they're not good
at creative abilities.

00:11:11.010 --> 00:11:12.790
But there has been
exponential progress.

00:11:12.790 --> 00:11:16.240
So there's still a significant
distance here they note.

00:11:16.240 --> 00:11:19.570
But their concern is
that is on the way,

00:11:19.570 --> 00:11:23.590
and it's going to disrupt
a lot of employment

00:11:23.590 --> 00:11:25.720
in the economy over time.

00:11:25.720 --> 00:11:33.160
And then they argue that given
that exponential advance,

00:11:33.160 --> 00:11:36.130
there are two fundamental
strategies in response.

00:11:36.130 --> 00:11:41.140
One is an organizational
innovation strategy.

00:11:41.140 --> 00:11:42.910
And the core idea
here is there's

00:11:42.910 --> 00:11:44.980
an opportunity for
creative entrepreneurs

00:11:44.980 --> 00:11:51.190
that can create new business
models that combine the growing

00:11:51.190 --> 00:11:56.320
numbers of mid-skilled workers
with ever-cheaper technologies

00:11:56.320 --> 00:11:58.270
to create new kinds of value.

00:11:58.270 --> 00:11:59.110
All right?

00:11:59.110 --> 00:12:02.320
That could be one way
out of this unemployment

00:12:02.320 --> 00:12:04.780
social disruption box.

00:12:04.780 --> 00:12:06.910
And they argue that
digital technologies

00:12:06.910 --> 00:12:08.980
do create great
opportunities for individuals

00:12:08.980 --> 00:12:13.780
to use their own kind
of unique capabilities.

00:12:13.780 --> 00:12:16.430
They ask, are we running
out of innovation?

00:12:16.430 --> 00:12:19.960
And when businesses are based
on bits instead of atoms,

00:12:19.960 --> 00:12:23.260
then each new product adds
to the set of building blocks

00:12:23.260 --> 00:12:25.570
that are available to
the next entrepreneur,

00:12:25.570 --> 00:12:28.240
instead of depleting
the stock of ideas.

00:12:28.240 --> 00:12:31.480
So this truly is an exponential
growth kind of territory.

00:12:31.480 --> 00:12:33.910
There's no denying
it, they argue.

00:12:33.910 --> 00:12:35.992
But it does create a new
set of building blocks

00:12:35.992 --> 00:12:37.450
that are potentially
available here

00:12:37.450 --> 00:12:40.030
that you can think about
organizational innovation

00:12:40.030 --> 00:12:41.800
to get around.

00:12:41.800 --> 00:12:43.960
The second argument
they make is that we

00:12:43.960 --> 00:12:47.410
need to make significant
investments in human capital

00:12:47.410 --> 00:12:52.240
as a way of dealing with
this oncoming set of issues.

00:12:52.240 --> 00:12:54.460
So improving the
education and skill sets

00:12:54.460 --> 00:12:58.990
to get the most out of our
kind of racing technology, they

00:12:58.990 --> 00:13:01.900
argue, is important.

00:13:01.900 --> 00:13:06.370
And they posit that there's
a third Industrial Revolution

00:13:06.370 --> 00:13:08.440
really around computing
and information,

00:13:08.440 --> 00:13:10.600
which is based on
information that,

00:13:10.600 --> 00:13:12.280
in effect, doesn't get used up.

00:13:15.090 --> 00:13:20.380
So that's Eric and
Andrew's picture.

00:13:20.380 --> 00:13:23.110
And it's a dark picture, right?

00:13:23.110 --> 00:13:24.962
Their concern is
that a lot of people

00:13:24.962 --> 00:13:26.170
are going to get left behind.

00:13:26.170 --> 00:13:29.860
Let's frantically do
organizational reforms,

00:13:29.860 --> 00:13:36.190
let's do other kinds of changes
in the educational system.

00:13:36.190 --> 00:13:40.360
They argue for a
set of tax changes.

00:13:40.360 --> 00:13:42.490
They really propose in the
end-- not in this piece,

00:13:42.490 --> 00:13:46.000
but in later pieces-- a negative
income tax to kind of redress

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:49.150
the inequality wealth
balance in the society.

00:13:49.150 --> 00:13:52.960
They're concerned that
this is upon us, right?

00:13:52.960 --> 00:13:55.720
And then David
Autor, MIT economist

00:13:55.720 --> 00:13:59.590
who's been doing some remarkable
work in a series of areas,

00:13:59.590 --> 00:14:01.972
we read his work
on manufacturing.

00:14:05.420 --> 00:14:08.720
He writes a responsive piece.

00:14:08.720 --> 00:14:12.130
Why are There
Still so Many Jobs?

00:14:12.130 --> 00:14:13.990
is his response.

00:14:13.990 --> 00:14:17.920
And he argues that Eric
and Andrew are only

00:14:17.920 --> 00:14:22.010
taking a partial look
at this phenomena.

00:14:22.010 --> 00:14:27.440
So let's do a little bit
of historical material.

00:14:27.440 --> 00:14:29.900
Historically,
economics has always

00:14:29.900 --> 00:14:32.480
found that technological
advance, historically,

00:14:32.480 --> 00:14:35.110
always creates net new jobs.

00:14:35.110 --> 00:14:37.860
And it's been going on since
the Industrial Revolution.

00:14:37.860 --> 00:14:41.900
And every time you study one of
these great ways of innovation,

00:14:41.900 --> 00:14:46.160
net, there are people affected,
disrupted by the new innovation

00:14:46.160 --> 00:14:47.480
waves, right?

00:14:47.480 --> 00:14:49.400
Buggy whip manufacturers
had a real problem

00:14:49.400 --> 00:14:51.650
with the advent of the
automobile internal combustion

00:14:51.650 --> 00:14:52.818
engine, right?

00:14:52.818 --> 00:14:54.860
So you can think about a
lot of displacement that

00:14:54.860 --> 00:14:58.250
has occurred historically, but
net, the amount of employment

00:14:58.250 --> 00:15:01.770
overall was a net gain.

00:15:01.770 --> 00:15:08.040
And David said, is that
era over, is the question.

00:15:08.040 --> 00:15:10.530
And his basic answer is no.

00:15:10.530 --> 00:15:11.970
That's not over.

00:15:11.970 --> 00:15:14.790
And what he would
argue, in a way,

00:15:14.790 --> 00:15:16.570
is an assessment and
counting problem.

00:15:16.570 --> 00:15:19.260
It's not that there is not
going to be disruption.

00:15:19.260 --> 00:15:28.320
It's just that automation
can also complement labor

00:15:28.320 --> 00:15:31.470
and can raise outputs
in ways that lead

00:15:31.470 --> 00:15:33.660
to higher demand for labor.

00:15:33.660 --> 00:15:34.290
Right?

00:15:34.290 --> 00:15:38.010
So automation does indeed
substitute for labor,

00:15:38.010 --> 00:15:42.210
but in this complimentary
way, automation

00:15:42.210 --> 00:15:47.400
can also lead to new
kinds of output, that lead

00:15:47.400 --> 00:15:48.690
to new kinds of employment.

00:15:48.690 --> 00:15:51.580
And you've got to
understand and assess that--

00:15:51.580 --> 00:15:53.890
the combination of these
factors, the substitution

00:15:53.890 --> 00:15:55.990
as well as the complementarity--

00:15:55.990 --> 00:15:59.590
in understanding what's
going to happen ahead.

00:15:59.590 --> 00:16:01.390
And he argues that
commentators tend

00:16:01.390 --> 00:16:04.180
to overstate the extent
of machine substitution

00:16:04.180 --> 00:16:07.840
for the human labor and ignore
the strong complementarities

00:16:07.840 --> 00:16:11.440
between automation and labor,
that in the end increase

00:16:11.440 --> 00:16:16.190
productivity, raise earnings,
and augment demand for labor.

00:16:16.190 --> 00:16:18.850
So there's one important
thing that has not changed

00:16:18.850 --> 00:16:21.690
in the economy here, right?

00:16:21.690 --> 00:16:27.820
So if we look at agriculture
in the 19th century,

00:16:27.820 --> 00:16:32.640
we employed approaching-- over
40% of our population in 1900

00:16:32.640 --> 00:16:34.870
was employed in agriculture.

00:16:34.870 --> 00:16:36.960
Now, we employ less than 1%.

00:16:36.960 --> 00:16:39.510
Much greater output.

00:16:39.510 --> 00:16:42.110
So that's a story of
intense productivity gains.

00:16:45.260 --> 00:16:50.690
But agriculture is different
than the production of goods--

00:16:50.690 --> 00:16:53.480
non-agricultural goods.

00:16:53.480 --> 00:16:56.180
If you look at food
consumption per human being

00:16:56.180 --> 00:16:58.640
in the United States,
it's not very different

00:16:58.640 --> 00:17:01.520
now than it was in 1900.

00:17:01.520 --> 00:17:04.543
Even in America there's only so
many calories we can consume.

00:17:04.543 --> 00:17:05.710
I mean, we're working on it.

00:17:05.710 --> 00:17:09.349
But even here there are limits.

00:17:09.349 --> 00:17:13.790
That's not true in the
production of goods.

00:17:13.790 --> 00:17:18.550
We seem to have an insatiable
appetite for more goods.

00:17:18.550 --> 00:17:20.675
And occasionally a movement
will hit society like,

00:17:20.675 --> 00:17:21.800
let's get rid of our stuff.

00:17:21.800 --> 00:17:25.339
But it never last very long.

00:17:25.339 --> 00:17:27.780
So it's a different world.

00:17:27.780 --> 00:17:30.530
We can't make the
agricultural analogy

00:17:30.530 --> 00:17:33.440
to non-agricultural
good production, right?

00:17:33.440 --> 00:17:35.060
They're different worlds.

00:17:35.060 --> 00:17:37.070
And part of the
story that the David

00:17:37.070 --> 00:17:40.070
otter is attempting
to illustrate here

00:17:40.070 --> 00:17:42.080
is that the limit--

00:17:42.080 --> 00:17:44.120
there is no limit
on goods, all right?

00:17:44.120 --> 00:17:47.030
So that complementarity,
that combination

00:17:47.030 --> 00:17:51.980
of people and machines can lead
to new kinds of technologies,

00:17:51.980 --> 00:17:54.620
new kinds of advances,
new kinds of goods that

00:17:54.620 --> 00:17:56.720
fit evolving sets of needs.

00:17:59.400 --> 00:18:04.100
And he provides an interesting
example of complementarity.

00:18:04.100 --> 00:18:10.282
He notes that ATMs, the
cash machines in every bank

00:18:10.282 --> 00:18:11.990
that you know of, and
all over the place,

00:18:11.990 --> 00:18:15.350
they were introduced in 1970.

00:18:15.350 --> 00:18:18.980
The assumption at the time
was that, well, there's

00:18:18.980 --> 00:18:20.840
not going to be any
more bank tellers.

00:18:20.840 --> 00:18:23.150
That job is over, right?

00:18:23.150 --> 00:18:25.610
And there were a lot of those.

00:18:25.610 --> 00:18:32.510
But what ended up happening,
was that by 2010, there

00:18:32.510 --> 00:18:37.550
were actually somewhat more
bank tellers, but their job

00:18:37.550 --> 00:18:41.450
and been repurposed to not
just doing, counting up cash

00:18:41.450 --> 00:18:42.800
and handing it to customers.

00:18:42.800 --> 00:18:45.860
Their jobs got repurposed
into, frankly considerably more

00:18:45.860 --> 00:18:50.000
sophisticated, customer
service kind of job.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:54.980
So an upgrading of the skills
required in a way for that job,

00:18:54.980 --> 00:18:57.170
but no loss in employment.

00:18:57.170 --> 00:18:59.690
In fact, a very modest gain.

00:18:59.690 --> 00:19:01.640
Despite the fact that
everybody thought

00:19:01.640 --> 00:19:03.890
that sector was going to go.

00:19:03.890 --> 00:19:06.420
So he argues that
that's not unique.

00:19:06.420 --> 00:19:09.900
This is going to occur
in other sectors as well.

00:19:09.900 --> 00:19:11.990
So the gains in
productivity have not

00:19:11.990 --> 00:19:14.670
led to a shortfall of demand
for goods and services.

00:19:14.670 --> 00:19:17.090
These keep growing,
which is a big offsetting

00:19:17.090 --> 00:19:23.710
factor to the substitution
of automation for work.

00:19:23.710 --> 00:19:25.670
And he provides an
interesting description

00:19:25.670 --> 00:19:28.550
of how you could look at
the different economies

00:19:28.550 --> 00:19:32.870
in recent decades,
right, the 1940 to 1970

00:19:32.870 --> 00:19:35.240
economy versus the
current economy.

00:19:35.240 --> 00:19:36.800
His characterization
of the economy

00:19:36.800 --> 00:19:40.460
that has been taking hold since
1980 through the current time,

00:19:40.460 --> 00:19:44.270
is that it's increasingly
professional and technical

00:19:44.270 --> 00:19:46.490
with managerial occupations,
and that they're

00:19:46.490 --> 00:19:48.380
growing pretty rapidly.

00:19:48.380 --> 00:19:51.830
Whereas skilled blue collar
occupations are shrinking,

00:19:51.830 --> 00:19:54.080
and that clerical and
sales occupations, which

00:19:54.080 --> 00:19:56.390
are the kind of vulnerable
equivalent of production

00:19:56.390 --> 00:19:59.490
jobs in the information
age, those are in decline.

