00:23:37.630 --> 00:23:40.300
between people and machines.

00:23:40.300 --> 00:23:42.370
And the comparative
advantage will

00:23:42.370 --> 00:23:45.310
allow computers to substitute
for workers in performing

00:23:45.310 --> 00:23:49.300
routine codifiable tasks.

00:23:49.300 --> 00:23:52.270
But it also amplifies
the comparative advantage

00:23:52.270 --> 00:23:55.450
of workers in supplying
problem solving skills,

00:23:55.450 --> 00:23:56.960
adaptability, and creativity.

00:23:56.960 --> 00:23:59.187
So the people-like capabilities.

00:23:59.187 --> 00:24:01.270
And maybe computers will
get to these some decade,

00:24:01.270 --> 00:24:05.060
but that's not happening
anytime real soon.

00:24:05.060 --> 00:24:09.190
So re-addressing the
balance between those two

00:24:09.190 --> 00:24:14.140
is the key to managing the
entry of these new IT-based

00:24:14.140 --> 00:24:17.590
technologies into the economy,
David Autor would argue.

00:24:17.590 --> 00:24:19.630
The frontier of
automation, he recognizes,

00:24:19.630 --> 00:24:22.540
is rapidly advancing.

00:24:22.540 --> 00:24:27.340
So the challenge of substituting
machines remains intense.

00:24:27.340 --> 00:24:31.360
But if you focus
only on what's lost,

00:24:31.360 --> 00:24:34.300
you miss a really central
economic mechanism.

00:24:34.300 --> 00:24:37.300
So automation affects
the demand for labor

00:24:37.300 --> 00:24:40.210
by raising the
value of the tasks

00:24:40.210 --> 00:24:44.650
that workers uniquely
supply, right?

00:24:44.650 --> 00:24:52.650
So that's-- Eric and Andrew tell
