because governments now might
not be adequate at this,

00:48:29.720 --> 00:48:31.220
will need to figure
out key business

00:48:31.220 --> 00:48:35.150
opportunities for
micro entrepreneurs

00:48:35.150 --> 00:48:37.760
that could give them
sustainable income,

00:48:37.760 --> 00:48:40.240
and give them the
ability to capital lines

00:48:40.240 --> 00:48:45.140
so that they'd be able to
generate wealth and create

00:48:45.140 --> 00:48:47.360
businesses in areas that
need these businesses.

00:48:47.360 --> 00:48:49.220
Because I think a lot of the
problem is in businesses.

00:48:49.220 --> 00:48:50.320
Like, you start a business
and you don't know

00:48:50.320 --> 00:48:51.440
if you will succeed or not.

00:48:51.440 --> 00:48:52.940
But if somebody
could do an analysis

00:48:52.940 --> 00:48:55.100
like they do for McDonald's,
where it's like, OK,

00:48:55.100 --> 00:48:56.490
we know this area this
will be successful.

00:48:56.490 --> 00:48:57.160
We know there's a need.

00:48:57.160 --> 00:48:59.320
The government probably
knows where there's needs.

00:48:59.320 --> 00:49:01.028
If you can do an
analysis to figure out--

00:49:01.028 --> 00:49:02.870
data to figure
out, OK, a company

00:49:02.870 --> 00:49:04.160
that does this would
be really useful here,

00:49:04.160 --> 00:49:06.180
a company that does this
would be really useful here.

00:49:06.180 --> 00:49:07.472
These will be the requirements.

00:49:07.472 --> 00:49:11.000
You can do a franchise model
for people to start companies.

00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:13.340
I'm not against like
universal basic income.

00:49:13.340 --> 00:49:15.523
I just worry about the
incentives of not having

00:49:15.523 --> 00:49:17.440
the ability-- or maybe
you create an incentive

00:49:17.440 --> 00:49:20.050
that you study and
you become a teacher.

00:49:20.050 --> 00:49:23.000
It's a thing that, no
matter what you say--

00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:26.270
I can say like what it is, but
it's more about how you do it.

00:49:26.270 --> 00:49:27.980
Because you could
incentivize and create

00:49:27.980 --> 00:49:30.215
more teachers, but if you
don't respect those teachers,

00:49:30.215 --> 00:49:32.270
or if they don't value them,
then it'll be very weird.

00:49:32.270 --> 00:49:34.220
If you create it and
people just use the money

00:49:34.220 --> 00:49:36.137
and build these businesses,
and they're really

00:49:36.137 --> 00:49:39.270
going out and having
fun, I don't know.

00:49:39.270 --> 00:49:41.630
AUDIENCE: I think for me,
universal basic income is one

00:49:41.630 --> 00:49:43.922
of those things where like
economists really talk about

00:49:43.922 --> 00:49:52.110
and we can, in a sense, there's
like a lot of literature

00:49:52.110 --> 00:49:55.290
and kind of journal articles
kind of fielding this idea like

00:49:55.290 --> 00:49:57.340
what if we don't.

00:49:57.340 --> 00:49:58.897
But in the US,
I'm trying to see,

00:49:58.897 --> 00:50:01.230
if we have this sort of
widening of this barbell effect,

00:50:01.230 --> 00:50:03.622
where we had this erosion
of this middle class,

00:50:03.622 --> 00:50:04.830
and kind of like this large--

00:50:08.150 --> 00:50:11.400
like, basically the
people getting rich

00:50:11.400 --> 00:50:13.950
aren't increasing in
number fast enough,

00:50:13.950 --> 00:50:15.510
but like, there's
a lot of people

00:50:15.510 --> 00:50:17.070
kind of regressing this way.

00:50:17.070 --> 00:50:19.830
And so I'm trying to see like,
what are the conditions that

00:50:19.830 --> 00:50:22.858
will allow for us to call
for a universal basic income?

00:50:22.858 --> 00:50:24.900
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Rashid,
I think you're really

00:50:24.900 --> 00:50:27.540
onto an important point here.

00:50:27.540 --> 00:50:34.230
If you've got a declining
middle class, their incentives

00:50:34.230 --> 00:50:38.190
to, in effect, take money
out of their own incomes

00:50:38.190 --> 00:50:41.063
and redistribute them,
that's going to be a problem.

00:50:41.063 --> 00:50:43.230
If that's a threatened
community, which increasingly

00:50:43.230 --> 00:50:48.480
it is, then politically, that is
a very difficult step to take.

00:50:48.480 --> 00:50:51.120
So I would argue
that we probably

00:50:51.120 --> 00:50:53.340
need to look at education,
which is a great way

00:50:53.340 --> 00:50:56.820
to lead into our next reading.

00:50:56.820 --> 00:51:00.750
So another terrific
David Autor piece.

00:51:00.750 --> 00:51:03.090
David, for my money is doing
the best work in economics

00:51:03.090 --> 00:51:03.968
anywhere.

00:51:06.960 --> 00:51:10.800
This is his-- this builds
on the Goldin and Katz piece

00:51:10.800 --> 00:51:12.510
that we talked about
in the last class,

00:51:12.510 --> 00:51:15.600
right, and kind of takes it
another kind of step further.

00:51:18.410 --> 00:51:22.710
And this piece is
all about skills,

00:51:22.710 --> 00:51:27.100
and education, and the rise
of earnings inequality.

00:51:27.100 --> 00:51:33.720
And now, there is a
steep and persistent rise

00:51:33.720 --> 00:51:35.430
of earnings inequality
in the US labor

00:51:35.430 --> 00:51:37.770
market that has been going
on for more than a couple

00:51:37.770 --> 00:51:39.840
of decades now.

00:51:39.840 --> 00:51:41.730
And it's not just true
in the United States.

00:51:41.730 --> 00:51:47.370
This is a phenomenon in the
developed world in general.

00:51:47.370 --> 00:51:48.942
But why look at inequality?

00:51:51.520 --> 00:51:53.760
And what do we start to see?

00:51:53.760 --> 00:51:56.940
First, the earnings
premium for education

00:51:56.940 --> 00:52:03.810
has risen very significantly
as we talked about last week.

00:52:03.810 --> 00:52:07.940
So 2/3 of the overall rise of
earning dispersion between 1980

00:52:07.940 --> 00:52:11.780
and 2005 is accounted for by
this increased premium that's

00:52:11.780 --> 00:52:14.300
associated with
schooling in general,

00:52:14.300 --> 00:52:17.390
and post-secondary
education in particular.

00:52:17.390 --> 00:52:20.640
So let me just jump
to a slide of this.

00:52:20.640 --> 00:52:22.730
So this is a projection
that comes out

00:52:22.730 --> 00:52:24.710
of the quite respected
Georgetown University

00:52:24.710 --> 00:52:26.540
Center on Education
and Workforce, which

00:52:26.540 --> 00:52:31.280
does really first-rate
work on the workforce.

00:52:31.280 --> 00:52:36.500
And they found that looking at
what projections were for 2024,

00:52:36.500 --> 00:52:40.130
they found that in
terms of job openings,

00:52:40.130 --> 00:52:42.740
high school diploma and less
than a high school diploma

00:52:42.740 --> 00:52:45.320
was going to be about
19.7 million job

00:52:45.320 --> 00:52:47.960
openings in that time period.

00:52:47.960 --> 00:52:51.140
Job openings for those with
college associate degrees--

00:52:51.140 --> 00:52:55.100
some college associate degrees
and college plus college--

00:52:55.100 --> 00:52:57.830
36.5 million jobs, right?

00:52:57.830 --> 00:53:02.540
So this is a profound
upskilling of the workforce

00:53:02.540 --> 00:53:04.700
that's going on.

00:53:04.700 --> 00:53:07.970
And look, by the way, the
higher education system

00:53:07.970 --> 00:53:11.190
isn't necessarily going
to produce these numbers.

00:53:11.190 --> 00:53:13.737
So what that means is that
the people on this end

00:53:13.737 --> 00:53:16.070
are going to be able to charge
a premium because there's

00:53:16.070 --> 00:53:18.560
going to be a shortage of
demand for their skill sets.

00:53:18.560 --> 00:53:19.730
That's what's going on.

00:53:19.730 --> 00:53:21.170
That's what David
Autor is telling

00:53:21.170 --> 00:53:26.270
us has been going on now for
several decades in the US.

00:53:26.270 --> 00:53:30.020
It's exactly that phenomena.

00:53:30.020 --> 00:53:37.930
And the earnings gap, then,
between college and high school

00:53:37.930 --> 00:53:40.270
graduates has more than
doubled in the United States

00:53:40.270 --> 00:53:43.340
over the last three decades.

00:53:43.340 --> 00:53:47.000
So lifetime earnings expectation
with a college degree

00:53:47.000 --> 00:53:50.540
is now very powerful compared
to your lifetime earning

00:53:50.540 --> 00:53:55.400
expectation if you have
a high school degree.

00:53:55.400 --> 00:53:59.780
And the skill
premium concept here,

00:53:59.780 --> 00:54:03.950
offers real insight into
the evolution of inequality

00:54:03.950 --> 00:54:04.700
in the US society.

00:54:04.700 --> 00:54:08.750
Now of course, this is all
related to the employment

00:54:08.750 --> 00:54:11.390
issues, and particularly
the future employment

00:54:11.390 --> 00:54:15.580
issues that we've just
been talking about.

00:54:15.580 --> 00:54:18.460
One more statistic
that underscores this.

00:54:18.460 --> 00:54:20.185
This is the fall
in real earnings.

00:54:22.790 --> 00:54:27.760
In a Hamilton project study
that was done for Brookings,

00:54:27.760 --> 00:54:30.040
this is the percentage
of real earnings

00:54:30.040 --> 00:54:38.370
in working age from 1990 to
2013 for men aged 30 to 45.

00:54:38.370 --> 00:54:41.490
No high school diploma,
median income decline

00:54:41.490 --> 00:54:44.880
went down 20 points
in that time period.

00:54:44.880 --> 00:54:50.570
High school diploma down 13
points in that time period.

00:54:50.570 --> 00:54:53.570
So we've got a profound
societal issue.

00:54:53.570 --> 00:54:58.070
This is just a big signal
of an inequality problem

00:54:58.070 --> 00:55:01.340
that's a problem now, and
because of the phenomenon

00:55:01.340 --> 00:55:05.990
we've just been talking about
in two previous readings.

00:55:05.990 --> 00:55:09.510
Is potentially going to get
significantly worse over time.

00:55:09.510 --> 00:55:11.360
So this is a big
societal dilemma

00:55:11.360 --> 00:55:14.750
that you guys are going to
have to figure out, right?

00:55:14.750 --> 00:55:19.970
And it looks like Autor is
telling us that a lot of this

00:55:19.970 --> 00:55:21.980
has to do with the
education system.

00:55:21.980 --> 00:55:23.900
How are we going to
alter the education

00:55:23.900 --> 00:55:28.940
system to move a lot of people
to higher levels of education?

00:55:28.940 --> 00:55:30.980
How is that phenomenon
going to work?

00:55:30.980 --> 00:55:33.170
What are we going to do
in terms of designing

00:55:33.170 --> 00:55:37.140
new institutions and new
mechanisms to do that?

00:55:37.140 --> 00:55:40.310
So the rising demand
for educated labor

00:55:40.310 --> 00:55:45.590
in advanced economies, including
the US, it's a profound rise.

00:55:45.590 --> 00:55:47.540
And if the supply
of educated workers

00:55:47.540 --> 00:55:50.660
doesn't keep pace with the
persistent outward shifts

00:55:50.660 --> 00:55:54.140
in demand for the
skills, then you just

00:55:54.140 --> 00:55:58.580
multiply your
inequality problem.

00:55:58.580 --> 00:56:06.540
And it forces a public policy
response around upskilling,

00:56:06.540 --> 00:56:07.040
right?

00:56:07.040 --> 00:56:10.190
That's a societal task we're
going to have to accomplish.

00:56:10.190 --> 00:56:13.730
Now, Rashid pointed out,
I think very astutely,

00:56:13.730 --> 00:56:16.760
that, with this
barbell phenomena,

00:56:16.760 --> 00:56:19.970
which is another David
Autor concept, right,

00:56:19.970 --> 00:56:22.220
that the society looks
increasingly like a barbell.

00:56:22.220 --> 00:56:26.360
You've got a very successful
and growing upper middle class,

00:56:26.360 --> 00:56:28.410
you've got the middle
of the economy,

00:56:28.410 --> 00:56:31.130
which is being in
decline and being--

00:56:31.130 --> 00:56:33.440
we just saw the
median income data--

00:56:33.440 --> 00:56:38.690
and moving towards lower-end
service delivery jobs, right?

00:56:38.690 --> 00:56:43.880
Personal service delivery
kinds of positions.

00:56:43.880 --> 00:56:48.740
The politics of that make
it problematic to deal with,

00:56:48.740 --> 00:56:51.050
say income distribution
in the United States.

00:56:51.050 --> 00:56:54.170
It's just not going to
be politically simple.

00:56:54.170 --> 00:56:55.910
If everybody was
rising together that's

00:56:55.910 --> 00:56:57.670
an easier problem to tackle.

00:56:57.670 --> 00:56:59.600
But they're not.

00:56:59.600 --> 00:57:02.450
So education is probably
the way in which we're

00:57:02.450 --> 00:57:04.150
going to have to address this.

00:57:04.150 --> 00:57:04.872
All right?

00:57:04.872 --> 00:57:06.830
We're going to have to
up skill that workforce.

00:57:06.830 --> 00:57:10.260
And look, by doing that,
as Martin pointed out,

00:57:10.260 --> 00:57:12.050
you're addressing the
underlying problem.

00:57:12.050 --> 00:57:14.750
You're helping people
realize their talents

00:57:14.750 --> 00:57:16.940
and their capabilities, right?

00:57:16.940 --> 00:57:20.540
And that's, frankly,
a better solution

00:57:20.540 --> 00:57:22.880
to the problem than just
throwing money at people,

00:57:22.880 --> 00:57:24.020
I would argue, right?

00:57:24.020 --> 00:57:25.730
It's probably not the
only thing you do,

00:57:25.730 --> 00:57:27.920
and it's not going
to help everybody,

00:57:27.920 --> 00:57:32.630
but can we find
strategies to do this?

00:57:32.630 --> 00:57:35.750
So I've been working on this,
and I've been thinking about it

00:57:35.750 --> 00:57:41.720
and talking to Sanjay Sarma,
who runs the online education

00:57:41.720 --> 00:57:46.820
effort at MIT, and MIT has
developed these new platform

00:57:46.820 --> 00:57:47.700
technologies.

00:57:47.700 --> 00:57:51.200
MITx and edX is another
platform provider,

00:57:51.200 --> 00:57:53.840
pervasive online capability.

00:57:53.840 --> 00:57:57.350
But on the other hand,
it's hard to envision

00:57:57.350 --> 00:57:59.480
a steelworker in
southeastern Ohio

00:57:59.480 --> 00:58:04.080
who's lost their job, at
being willing or able to spend

00:58:04.080 --> 00:58:06.620
a substantial amount of
time in front of a computer

00:58:06.620 --> 00:58:09.037
blue screen in their basement
while their kids are running

00:58:09.037 --> 00:58:10.100
around upstairs, right?

00:58:10.100 --> 00:58:11.342
Just not terribly likely.

00:58:11.342 --> 00:58:13.550
AUDIENCE: Or, if there was
a case brought up recently

00:58:13.550 --> 00:58:15.820
that somebody was worried about
losing their job because they

00:58:15.820 --> 00:58:17.860
would lose their insurance,
and their kid might not be

00:58:17.860 --> 00:58:19.040
able to get proper [INAUDIBLE].

00:58:19.040 --> 00:58:20.582
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
Yes, the problems

00:58:20.582 --> 00:58:22.960
multiply when you
get into this box.

00:58:22.960 --> 00:58:25.820
And we've had two
recent-- recently two

00:58:25.820 --> 00:58:28.130
very interesting
books that start

00:58:28.130 --> 00:58:32.580
to portray this problem for us.

00:58:32.580 --> 00:58:38.570
And so Hillbillology is a
very interesting story of one

00:58:38.570 --> 00:58:43.430
of the big diasporas in US
history out of the South,

00:58:43.430 --> 00:58:47.570
out of the Appalachians,
into industrial employment

00:58:47.570 --> 00:58:49.070
in the Middle West.

00:58:49.070 --> 00:58:51.020
And with the decline
of US manufacturing,

00:58:51.020 --> 00:58:53.450
that community
really got nailed.

00:58:53.450 --> 00:58:55.410
And what do you do
with that community?

00:58:55.410 --> 00:58:58.190
This book is a pay-on
to that community,

00:58:58.190 --> 00:59:00.980
and how to even think
about the kind of problems

00:59:00.980 --> 00:59:02.120
they've got into.

00:59:02.120 --> 00:59:05.060
Opioids are one example
cited in that book.

00:59:05.060 --> 00:59:10.910
There's a new book just
out by Annie Goldstein

00:59:10.910 --> 00:59:16.550
about a town in Wisconsin.

00:59:16.550 --> 00:59:18.800
Town of about 60,000 people.

00:59:18.800 --> 00:59:21.785
The major employer was
a General Motors plant

00:59:21.785 --> 00:59:24.110
that employed 9,000 people.

00:59:24.110 --> 00:59:26.690
It had survived the Rust
Belt. It was a quality plant.

00:59:26.690 --> 00:59:30.740
But when General Motors
went bankrupt in 2008,

00:59:30.740 --> 00:59:33.980
all those people lost their
jobs, every single one of them.

00:59:33.980 --> 00:59:36.470
And it put that community--

00:59:36.470 --> 00:59:38.840
tax revenues declined,
housing values

00:59:38.840 --> 00:59:41.690
declined, everything
is going down, right?

00:59:41.690 --> 00:59:46.590
Community services collapse,
charitable contributions drop,

00:59:46.590 --> 00:59:48.500
right?

00:59:48.500 --> 00:59:51.410
It's painful to watch what
happens in that community.

00:59:51.410 --> 00:59:53.390
Finally, one good thing happens.

00:59:53.390 --> 00:59:56.630
Dollar store opens a
distribution plant.

00:59:56.630 --> 00:59:58.460
The jobs pay way less
than half of what

00:59:58.460 --> 01:00:01.010
the General Motors jobs paid.

01:00:01.010 --> 01:00:03.640
So that's the kind of problem
that we're up against here.

01:00:03.640 --> 01:00:05.510
And in light of all
we've just been talking

01:00:05.510 --> 01:00:07.910
about technological job
displacement occurring

01:00:07.910 --> 01:00:11.810
over time, we've got
a big upskilling job

01:00:11.810 --> 01:00:15.320
to do here, I would
argue, in our economy.

01:00:15.320 --> 01:00:20.180
So online capabilities are
one piece, but that's not

01:00:20.180 --> 01:00:21.520
going to be the answer here.

01:00:21.520 --> 01:00:23.270
It's probably going
to be a blended model.

01:00:23.270 --> 01:00:26.600
And can we think about how
to enlist community colleges,

01:00:26.600 --> 01:00:29.600
and how to join them
with universities

01:00:29.600 --> 01:00:30.680
developing curriculum?

01:00:30.680 --> 01:00:32.750
And how do we know
what the curriculum is?

01:00:32.750 --> 01:00:36.200
What's the content education
in a society that's going

01:00:36.200 --> 01:00:38.000
to change the nature of work?

01:00:38.000 --> 01:00:39.560
How do we begin to
understand that?

01:00:39.560 --> 01:00:41.990
What's the changing nature of
work that these technologies

01:00:41.990 --> 01:00:43.290
are going to drive?

01:00:43.290 --> 01:00:44.450
How do we educate for that?

01:00:44.450 --> 01:00:46.940
So we've got a big task ahead.

01:00:46.940 --> 01:00:49.050
But a mix of employers,
community colleges,

01:00:49.050 --> 01:00:51.560
universities, and
labor organizations

01:00:51.560 --> 01:00:54.140
is probably going to be the way
we try to figure some of this

01:00:54.140 --> 01:00:55.100
out.

01:00:55.100 --> 01:00:58.850
So I'm just extrapolating
from David Autor's point

01:00:58.850 --> 01:01:01.070
about the underlying
importance of education

01:01:01.070 --> 01:01:03.867
to this inequality
problem, and emphasizing

01:01:03.867 --> 01:01:05.450
that education is
probably going to be

01:01:05.450 --> 01:01:07.580
the fix we're going to use.

01:01:07.580 --> 01:01:09.380
But then, how are going
to do that, right?

01:01:09.380 --> 01:01:11.420
So a big challenging problem.

01:01:11.420 --> 01:01:13.867
So who's got this one?

01:01:13.867 --> 01:01:15.950
Sanam, you want to lead
us through some questions?

01:01:15.950 --> 01:01:17.723
AUDIENCE: Sure.

01:01:17.723 --> 01:01:18.890
Yeah, so a couple of points.

01:01:18.890 --> 01:01:20.630
I thought the
focus on inequality

01:01:20.630 --> 01:01:23.000
was really interesting
here, especially

01:01:23.000 --> 01:01:26.690
he touches on briefly why
inequality is actually

01:01:26.690 --> 01:01:27.733
good for innovation.

01:01:27.733 --> 01:01:29.150
And this is something
that we talk

01:01:29.150 --> 01:01:32.640
a lot of that in econ classes,
and how, of course there

01:01:32.640 --> 01:01:34.430
are greater
incentives to be more

01:01:34.430 --> 01:01:36.980
productive because the rewards
and returns are better.

01:01:36.980 --> 01:01:39.410
And then also,
generally in countries

01:01:39.410 --> 01:01:43.942
that have more unequal
distributions of income,

01:01:43.942 --> 01:01:45.650
