01:08:56.189 --> 01:08:58.770
The way in which they have
been excluded in, say, Brazil,

01:08:58.770 --> 01:09:01.750
from accessing education
because of their race.

01:09:01.750 --> 01:09:02.250
Right?

01:09:02.250 --> 01:09:04.170
So that's a very
complicated picture.

01:09:04.170 --> 01:09:08.680
But what we can determine
is that because families,

01:09:08.680 --> 01:09:12.270
in sort of the middle and
upper class in Brazil,

01:09:12.270 --> 01:09:14.470
have always had
access to education,

01:09:14.470 --> 01:09:17.189
they want to sustain
that standard of living

01:09:17.189 --> 01:09:18.359
for their progeny.

01:09:18.359 --> 01:09:20.520
And so then their
progeny gets educated.

01:09:20.520 --> 01:09:23.160
But at the same
time, there's only so

01:09:23.160 --> 01:09:25.402
many spots at the national
universities, right?

01:09:25.402 --> 01:09:26.819
And so those spots
are never going

01:09:26.819 --> 01:09:30.359
to go to the children of
the low income parents.

01:09:30.359 --> 01:09:32.910
They're always going to go
to the wealthier families.

01:09:32.910 --> 01:09:36.297
And if we think about things in
a process of social exclusion

01:09:36.297 --> 01:09:38.130
rather than inequality,
which is the outcome

01:09:38.130 --> 01:09:42.000
of social exclusion, I think
we can start rectifying some--

01:09:42.000 --> 01:09:44.760
at least some of the
dimensions by which

01:09:44.760 --> 01:09:46.200
we oppress other people.

01:09:46.200 --> 01:09:48.810
Because it's really easy to
say, oh, there's inequalities,

01:09:48.810 --> 01:09:50.560
and to identify all of them.

01:09:50.560 --> 01:09:52.109
But I think it's
much harder to think

01:09:52.109 --> 01:09:54.090
