01:12:57.360 --> 01:12:59.027
And they explained
it in terms of, well,

01:12:59.027 --> 01:13:00.585
we built the road, right?

01:13:00.585 --> 01:13:02.460
But when we were giving
out these securities,

01:13:02.460 --> 01:13:04.460
we didn't make decision
put our money into them.

01:13:04.460 --> 01:13:06.150
It was all these
people were trying to--

01:13:06.150 --> 01:13:08.160
they thought that this
was the factor to success

01:13:08.160 --> 01:13:09.210
and kept buying them
and buying them.

01:13:09.210 --> 01:13:10.560
Every time they bought one
they would crack the road,

01:13:10.560 --> 01:13:11.852
crack the road, crack the road.

01:13:11.852 --> 01:13:14.760
But we had the duty to give
certain kinds of bonds,

01:13:14.760 --> 01:13:17.880
and other people sold them
again, which we didn't do.

01:13:17.880 --> 01:13:21.143
And so ultimately we get--

01:13:21.143 --> 01:13:23.810
it's easy to point the finger at
us because the road was broken.

01:13:23.810 --> 01:13:25.602
But it's because the
actions of individuals

01:13:25.602 --> 01:13:28.940
buying, and buying, and
buying, going into grief.

01:13:28.940 --> 01:13:31.380
And so I think that's
an interesting point.

01:13:31.380 --> 01:13:32.940
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: So that
is an example of a bubble

01:13:32.940 --> 01:13:33.480
economy [INAUDIBLE].

01:13:33.480 --> 01:13:34.355
AUDIENCE: A bubble
economy, yeah.

01:13:34.355 --> 01:13:35.410
And also this point--

01:13:35.410 --> 01:13:37.160
and I think Stephanie's point--

01:13:37.160 --> 01:13:38.110
I forget which one--

01:13:38.110 --> 01:13:41.400
on, oh, the insurance policy
was made by Peter Thiel

01:13:41.400 --> 01:13:44.440
in 2010 about why--

01:13:44.440 --> 01:13:46.200
he questioned if
you go to college

01:13:46.200 --> 01:13:48.740
would you be better off?

01:13:48.740 --> 01:13:51.270
And so that's not an
inequality of education.

01:13:51.270 --> 01:13:55.110
On the issue of inequity what
I find really interesting

01:13:55.110 --> 01:13:58.290
is that we talk about
equality, but we're

01:13:58.290 --> 01:14:00.930
living in a relatively
prosperous time.

01:14:00.930 --> 01:14:03.343
Also, the US, it is a
land of opportunity.

01:14:03.343 --> 01:14:05.760
And so I thought it was really
interesting, or even ironic

01:14:05.760 --> 01:14:07.560
during the 1%
movement, that it was

01:14:07.560 --> 01:14:11.370
like the 1% of the world
getting angry at the 1%.

01:14:11.370 --> 01:14:13.380
And it is this
thing that we have

01:14:13.380 --> 01:14:15.500
this kind of social
contract that in the US

01:14:15.500 --> 01:14:19.300
you will be able to
advance and move forward.

01:14:19.300 --> 01:14:21.040
But I think inequity
is a big issue.

01:14:21.040 --> 01:14:23.550
Like, how do you make it
so that people can move up?

01:14:23.550 --> 01:14:26.160
Warren Buffett talks
about the lottery of life.

01:14:26.160 --> 01:14:29.100
That say you were about to
be born in five minutes.

01:14:29.100 --> 01:14:31.490
If you had to design
the world any which way,

01:14:31.490 --> 01:14:32.360
and you don't know
if you're going

01:14:32.360 --> 01:14:33.710
to be born a woman,
a man, if you're

01:14:33.710 --> 01:14:35.460
going to be born
disabled, if you're going

01:14:35.460 --> 01:14:37.140
to be born mentally retarded.

01:14:37.140 --> 01:14:37.330
AUDIENCE: With a
mental disability.

01:14:37.330 --> 01:14:39.150
AUDIENCE: Or if you're
going to be born--

01:14:39.150 --> 01:14:40.060
you know what I mean.

01:14:40.060 --> 01:14:42.060
If you would be born
somewhere else in the world

01:14:42.060 --> 01:14:43.200
where you don't
have an opportunity

01:14:43.200 --> 01:14:45.575
and you have to pick up scraps
for the rest of your life.

01:14:45.575 --> 01:14:47.840
What kind of world would
you want to create,

01:14:47.840 --> 01:14:50.168
and how do you go
building about that world?

01:14:50.168 --> 01:14:51.960
And I think that's a
really interesting way

01:14:51.960 --> 01:14:52.830
of looking at it.

01:14:52.830 --> 01:14:55.550
Because really, I don't think
equal outcome I don't think

01:14:55.550 --> 01:14:56.670
will ever be a thing.

01:14:56.670 --> 01:14:59.370
And to say that that will be
a thing is a very flawed idea

01:14:59.370 --> 01:15:02.940
and would just
lead to self-anger,

01:15:02.940 --> 01:15:04.860
and you will get
jealousy of other people.

01:15:04.860 --> 01:15:07.620
There's also things in
life that you can't buy.

01:15:07.620 --> 01:15:09.510
If you focus on
building that, if you

01:15:09.510 --> 01:15:12.360
build great relationships,
if you're good to people

01:15:12.360 --> 01:15:13.710
they'll be good to you.

01:15:13.710 --> 01:15:15.252
Because there's a
lot of billionaires

01:15:15.252 --> 01:15:16.770
that everybody hates them.

01:15:16.770 --> 01:15:19.710
You can look at the
President, right?

01:15:19.710 --> 01:15:22.013
And so I think
that's a big issue.

01:15:22.013 --> 01:15:23.180
And there's just been that--

01:15:23.180 --> 01:15:25.290
well, there's also the idea
of a capitalist society

01:15:25.290 --> 01:15:26.850
where we have to have
these figureheads that

01:15:26.850 --> 01:15:27.683
made a lot of money.

01:15:27.683 --> 01:15:29.350
And we have to have
the proper incentive

01:15:29.350 --> 01:15:30.690
to want to become like them.

01:15:30.690 --> 01:15:31.800
And we have to push that--

01:15:31.800 --> 01:15:34.750
that's why the system is built
for us to want to revere people

01:15:34.750 --> 01:15:37.710
on the Forbes list, so
that we can continue

01:15:37.710 --> 01:15:39.270
growing capitalistically.

01:15:39.270 --> 01:15:40.650
But I think definitely what
will happen-- especially

01:15:40.650 --> 01:15:42.108
my generation-- is
people are going

01:15:42.108 --> 01:15:44.490
to start to question capitalism,
especially the issues

01:15:44.490 --> 01:15:45.578
that Marx brought up.

01:15:45.578 --> 01:15:47.370
So that we'll say, how
do we build a better

01:15:47.370 --> 01:15:52.090
capitalist system where
we can be better humans?

01:15:52.090 --> 01:15:55.162
Or there might be a lot
more assholes, I don't know.

01:15:55.162 --> 01:16:00.990
AUDIENCE: Also to Martin's
point about your college degree

01:16:00.990 --> 01:16:03.180
may not be the
right path, or it's

01:16:03.180 --> 01:16:06.240
kind of hazardous to say that if
we just give everyone a college

01:16:06.240 --> 01:16:08.183
degree and kind
of subsidize that,

01:16:08.183 --> 01:16:10.350
they'll just make higher
incomes and like everything

01:16:10.350 --> 01:16:11.310
will be fine.

01:16:11.310 --> 01:16:14.890
I think there's-- and I can't
remember which slide it was.

01:16:14.890 --> 01:16:18.565
Like, what percent-- like
what degree level and like

01:16:18.565 --> 01:16:19.690
how it affects your income.

01:16:19.690 --> 01:16:20.930
AUDIENCE: The change
in real earnings?

01:16:20.930 --> 01:16:22.763
AUDIENCE: Yeah, the
change in real earnings.

01:16:24.112 --> 01:16:25.320
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: This one?

01:16:25.320 --> 01:16:27.750
AUDIENCE: This one.

01:16:27.750 --> 01:16:29.030
AUDIENCE: Seems uneven.

01:16:29.030 --> 01:16:30.150
AUDIENCE: It seems uneven.

01:16:30.150 --> 01:16:35.520
But I think there's something
to be said about kind

01:16:35.520 --> 01:16:37.590
of generational nobility here.

01:16:37.590 --> 01:16:41.070
So like those who had a
bachelors degree coming out

01:16:41.070 --> 01:16:43.230
in maybe 1970 or a
little bit earlier,

01:16:43.230 --> 01:16:46.770
that income level was
relative to the time.

01:16:46.770 --> 01:16:48.930
Like, it allowed me
to live comfortably,

01:16:48.930 --> 01:16:51.153
whereas my bachelor's
degree now,

01:16:51.153 --> 01:16:53.070
and whatever bump in
income level I get, like,

01:16:53.070 --> 01:16:54.220
am I living comfortably?

01:16:54.220 --> 01:16:57.000
Am I going to be
able to subsist?

01:16:57.000 --> 01:16:58.977
And that might be
like an indicator

01:16:58.977 --> 01:17:00.810
where it's like, yeah,
it's unequal in here,

01:17:00.810 --> 01:17:03.360
but like there's actually a
bigger social problem here.

01:17:03.360 --> 01:17:06.990
So even though I might be
making more than I was in 1990,

01:17:06.990 --> 01:17:11.160
like is my 1990 salary, at
that level is it enough for me

01:17:11.160 --> 01:17:12.030
to live in 1990?

01:17:12.030 --> 01:17:14.060
And like, is my 2013
salary, is that enough?

01:17:14.060 --> 01:17:15.727
AUDIENCE: These are
real earning, right?

01:17:15.727 --> 01:17:18.100
So these are
inflation adjusting.

01:17:18.100 --> 01:17:18.600
Yeah.

01:17:18.600 --> 01:17:19.225
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:17:19.225 --> 01:17:21.355
Inflation adjusted, but
like cost of living.

01:17:21.355 --> 01:17:22.730
AUDIENCE: There's
also one factor

01:17:22.730 --> 01:17:24.240
I think is really important.

01:17:24.240 --> 01:17:26.550
And I think the recent
election showcased--

01:17:26.550 --> 01:17:27.250
were you done with your point?

01:17:27.250 --> 01:17:27.875
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:17:27.875 --> 01:17:28.937
No, I'm done.

01:17:28.937 --> 01:17:31.520
AUDIENCE: Which is, I think the
real issue happening right now

01:17:31.520 --> 01:17:34.640
is that we are in a stagnation
in terms of actual real term

01:17:34.640 --> 01:17:37.220
prospect-- like real
prosperity growth.

01:17:37.220 --> 01:17:41.090
The numbers can say we grew,
but everything costs a lot more.

01:17:41.090 --> 01:17:44.900
The way the system is
created to show that, oh,

01:17:44.900 --> 01:17:45.860
we're doing well.

01:17:45.860 --> 01:17:47.690
I think like the
poverty line, right,

01:17:47.690 --> 01:17:49.708
is flawed the way we're
calculating it now,

01:17:49.708 --> 01:17:51.500
because it's not really
showing what people

01:17:51.500 --> 01:17:52.820
can buy with what they have.

01:17:52.820 --> 01:17:55.070
And that's how we create it.

01:17:55.070 --> 01:17:57.620
Because everything costs a lot
more, but they've adjusted it

01:17:57.620 --> 01:17:59.453
and they've fudged the
numbers in such a way

01:17:59.453 --> 01:18:01.310
that it seems to be
kind of a big picture.

01:18:01.310 --> 01:18:01.940
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
So we're going to--

01:18:01.940 --> 01:18:03.440
Martin, we're going
to get into this

01:18:03.440 --> 01:18:05.232
when we get to the last
reading and lay out

01:18:05.232 --> 01:18:07.220
this whole issue of
secular stagnation,

01:18:07.220 --> 01:18:10.130
and what the implications
of that historically

01:18:10.130 --> 01:18:13.430
low productivity rate we're at,
and historically low investment

01:18:13.430 --> 01:18:15.260
rates that we're at.

01:18:15.260 --> 01:18:16.610
And that may be--

01:18:16.610 --> 01:18:18.440
I think you're about
to drive at this--

01:18:18.440 --> 01:18:23.280
that may be a really, big
time, near time problem.

01:18:23.280 --> 01:18:25.820
Whereas the technological job
displacement maybe a little

01:18:25.820 --> 01:18:26.665
further off.

01:18:26.665 --> 01:18:27.290
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:18:27.290 --> 01:18:27.930
AUDIENCE: Well,
yeah, I was going

01:18:27.930 --> 01:18:29.360
to finish with when
people don't see

01:18:29.360 --> 01:18:31.040
like what is going
to be the next step,

01:18:31.040 --> 01:18:32.150
they kind of start
to lose hope and they

01:18:32.150 --> 01:18:34.400
start fighting over things
that really are non-issues.

01:18:34.400 --> 01:18:36.858
This happens in a lot-- it's
a common organizational thing.

01:18:36.858 --> 01:18:38.240
When you lose your
vision, people

01:18:38.240 --> 01:18:39.615
start fighting
over really like--

01:18:39.615 --> 01:18:41.550
very intensely--
about things that

01:18:41.550 --> 01:18:43.640
maybe don't matter as
much, or wouldn't have been

01:18:43.640 --> 01:18:45.483
an issue when they had vision.

01:18:45.483 --> 01:18:47.150
And I think that's
one of the reasons we

01:18:47.150 --> 01:18:49.400
see such intense
infighting right now.

01:18:49.400 --> 01:18:51.928
Because we're really
starting to question

01:18:51.928 --> 01:18:53.720
like what will-- well,
not really question,

01:18:53.720 --> 01:18:54.960
but we should just
see America as it is,

01:18:54.960 --> 01:18:56.602
and no one has said
this what America

01:18:56.602 --> 01:18:58.060
will be 50 years
from now and we'll

01:18:58.060 --> 01:19:00.020
start working towards that.

01:19:00.020 --> 01:19:03.140
And I think that's a big factor
that I saw in the last four

01:19:03.140 --> 01:19:04.262
years.

01:19:04.262 --> 01:19:05.720
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
Sanam, you want

01:19:05.720 --> 01:19:09.290
to give us a closing point after
all of our discussions on this?

01:19:09.290 --> 01:19:11.330
AUDIENCE: There's a
slight point, I think.

01:19:11.330 --> 01:19:12.872
We might be able to
talk about later,

01:19:12.872 --> 01:19:14.690
but like the GI Bill as like--

01:19:14.690 --> 01:19:17.330
I wanted to mention it as
like the last big, kind

01:19:17.330 --> 01:19:19.730
of governmentally-subsidized,
like, real movement

01:19:19.730 --> 01:19:24.050
towards kind of educating
en masse a large subset

01:19:24.050 --> 01:19:28.370
of the population for
the sake of education

01:19:28.370 --> 01:19:29.870
and all the other reasons.

01:19:29.870 --> 01:19:32.670
But there's [INAUDIBLE]
if I didn't say,

01:19:32.670 --> 01:19:36.392
there's a whole subset of like
social inequities that exist

01:19:36.392 --> 01:19:38.725
within the GI Bill that we
don't have to get into, but--

01:19:38.725 --> 01:19:40.267
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
But you're right.

01:19:40.267 --> 01:19:43.490
I mean, the two mass
higher education

01:19:43.490 --> 01:19:46.760
bills that the US did--
so the Land Grant College

01:19:46.760 --> 01:19:50.750
Act that created, in effect, the
institutional base, and the GI

01:19:50.750 --> 01:19:54.560
Bill that took this huge
population returning from World

01:19:54.560 --> 01:19:57.230
War II and stuck
them in college,

01:19:57.230 --> 01:20:03.320
those created gigantic
returns for the society.

01:20:03.320 --> 01:20:06.710
So I understand
your point, Martin,

01:20:06.710 --> 01:20:09.680
which is that just
getting a college degree

01:20:09.680 --> 01:20:14.130
doesn't necessarily fit you
for the life worth living.

01:20:14.130 --> 01:20:15.780
I think we will
all agree on that.

01:20:15.780 --> 01:20:17.680
But it sure helps.

01:20:17.680 --> 01:20:18.847
It sure moves you a step up.

01:20:18.847 --> 01:20:20.305
AUDIENCE: Better
than [INAUDIBLE]..

01:20:20.305 --> 01:20:22.703
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: And
gets you closer in range.

01:20:22.703 --> 01:20:24.870
Sanam, how about a closing
thought from you on this,

01:20:24.870 --> 01:20:26.187
and we'll take a short break.

01:20:26.187 --> 01:20:28.520
AUDIENCE: I think it's a lot
of good points, definitely.

01:20:28.520 --> 01:20:31.730
And I think that when
we're thinking about policy

01:20:31.730 --> 01:20:34.190
and how to move
forward, the discussion

01:20:34.190 --> 01:20:38.150
about systems of
privilege and exclusion

01:20:38.150 --> 01:20:39.510
are really important as well.

01:20:39.510 --> 01:20:41.510
And also to think about
kind of like what can we

01:20:41.510 --> 01:20:44.434
define as success both
individually and as a system

01:20:44.434 --> 01:20:48.760
is also an interesting
and problematic thing

01:20:48.760 --> 01:20:51.580
that we should
continue to talk about.